[1] Case updates
- Thu 13 Dec 2018. Epidemiological situation report, DRC Ministry of Health
[in French, machine trans., abridged, edited]
https://us13.campaign-archive.com/?u=89e5755d2cca4840b1af93176&id=b19df2d61f

The epidemiological situation of the Ebola virus disease in the provinces of North Kivu and Ituri dated 12 Dec 2018:
- Since the beginning of the epidemic, the cumulative number of cases is 515, of which 467 are confirmed and 48 are probable. In total, there have been 303 deaths (255 confirmed and 48 probable) and 179 people recovered.
- 96 suspected cases are under investigation.
- 10 new confirmed cases have been reported, including 4 in Kyondo, 2 in Mabalako, 2 in Komanda, 1 in Kalunguta and 1 in Beni.
- The new case confirmed in Mabalako, reported in the bulletin of 12 Dec 2018, lives in the health area near Biena, where he began to have symptoms of Ebola. The patient was contaminated by a confirmed case who lived in Aloya City, Mabalako Health Zone, and died at the Ebola treatment center (ETC) on 3 Dec 2018.
- 7 new confirmed case deaths have been reported, including 2 in Kyondo, 2 in Katwa, 1 in Beni, 1 in Mabalako and 1 in Komanda. All are community deaths, except that in Beni.
- 4 new people have recovered, including 3 discharged from the ETC of Beni and 1 from the ETC of Butembo.

News of the response
----------------------
- The youngest patient recovering from Ebola was discharged from the Beni ETC this Wed 12 Dec 2018. This miraculously young child, born 31 Oct 2018, was admitted at the age of 6 days to the ETC after her mother, a confirmed case of Ebola, died during childbirth. Throughout the infant's hospitalization, pediatricians, resuscitators and nannies of ETC took turns at her bedside 24 hours a day to give her every chance to survive. Nannies are former ETC patients who have recovered from Ebola and are able to care for sick children by wearing lighter protective gear. They play a fundamental role in caring for sick children who need more attention and a reassuring presence at their side during treatment.

Vaccination
-----------
- Continued wide-belt vaccination (or ring plus) in Otomaber (in Komanda Health Zone) and Aloya (in Mabalako Health Zone).
- Since the start of vaccination on 8 Aug 2018, 45 647 people have been vaccinated, including 18 726 in Beni [North Kivu], 8084 in Katwa [North Kivu], 4950 in Mabalako [North Kivu], 4276 in Butembo [North Kivu], 2108 in Kalunguta [North Kivu], 1663 in Mandima [Ituri], 791 in Vuhovi [North Kivu], 750 in Masereka [North Kivu], 700 in Lubero [North Kivu], 633 in Komanda [Ituri], 627 in Oicha [North Kivu], 599 in Mutwanga [North Kivu], 434 in Bunia [Ituri], 381 in Kyondo [Uganda], 355 in Tchomia [Ituri], 314 in Musienene [North Kivu], 63 in Alimbongo [North Kivu], and 13 in Kisangani [Tshopo].

--
