- Wed 12 Dec 2018. Epidemiological situation report, DRC Ministry of Health [in French, machine trans., abridged, edited]
https://us13.campaign-archive.com/?u=89e5755d2cca4840b1af93176&id=0da99fb326

The epidemiological situation of the Ebola virus disease in the provinces of North Kivu and Ituri dated 11 Dec 2018:
- Since the beginning of the epidemic, the cumulative number of cases is 505, of which 457 are confirmed and 48 are probable. In total, there have been 298 deaths (250 confirmed and 48 probable) and 175 people recovered.
- 100 suspected cases are under investigation.
- 5 new confirmed cases have been reported, including 2 in Katwa, 1 in Komanda, 1 in Musienene and 1 in Mabalako.
- 9 new confirmed case deaths have been reported, including 6 in Beni, 1 in Butembo, 1 in Katwa (community deaths) and 1 in Mabalako.
- 3 new people have recovered and been discharged from Butembo ETC.

News of the response
----------------------
- An alert has been raised from the Rutshuru General Referral Hospital in Goma after a patient died in the hospital after presenting bleeding signs. A sample was taken, and the result of the laboratory test was negative.
- Contacts of a confirmed case from Beni traveling to Goma: The surveillance teams in Goma were looking for 6 people -- 3 adults and 3 children -- who had been in contact with a confirmed case from Beni. Before receiving the results of the laboratory tests of their deceased relative in Beni, these 6 contacts had started for Goma, traveling in 2 separate groups. They had to go to relatives living in Mabanga South, a district of Goma. A mother and her 2 children were found at Kanyabayonga on Tue 11 Dec 2018, and agreed to return to Beni to complete their 21-day follow-up period. The 2nd group of travelers, consisting of the other 2 adults with the 3rd child, arrived in South Mabanga on the night of Tue 11 Dec 2018. The child had a fever, and the 3 people were immediately transferred to the Goma ETC to perform the necessary tests. The laboratory test results were negative.

Vaccination
-----------
- Continued wide-belt vaccination (or ring plus) in Otomaber (in Komanda Health Zone) and Aloya (in Mabalako Health Zone).
- Since the start of vaccination on 8 Aug 2018, 45 020 people have been vaccinated, 18 638 in Beni [North Kivu], 7765 in Katwa [North Kivu], 4930 in Mabalako [North Kivu], 4276 in Butembo [North Kivu], 2108 in Kalunguta [North Kivu], 1663 in Mandima [Ituri] (see source URL for the complete list).

Sensitization
------------
Beyond the medical arsenal, the Ministry of Health recalls that the response against Ebola is above all community. Since the beginning of the epidemic, the city of Goma is an exposed area in the same way as the cities of Bunia and Kisangani because of the regular displacements of the population between the zones currently affected by the Ebola epidemic and these 3 large urban centers. If all the inhabitants of these cities respect the sanitary measures recommended by the Ministry of Health, it is possible to ensure that, even if an Ebola case arrives in the city, it would be a sporadic case and would not lead to a new outbreak.

As a reminder, the recommendations of the Ministry of Health are as follows:
1. Follow basic hygiene practices, including regular hand washing with soap and water or ashes;
2. If an acquaintance from an epidemic zone comes to visit you and is ill, do not touch them and call directly the North Kivu civil protection hotline;
3. If you are identified as an Ebola patient contact, agree to be vaccinated and followed for 21 days;
4. If a person dies because of Ebola, follow the instructions for safe and dignified burials. It is simply a funeral method that respects funerary customs and traditions while protecting the family and community from Ebola contamination.
5. For all health professionals, observe the hygiene measures in the health centers and declare any patient with symptoms of Ebola (fever, diarrhea, vomiting, fatigue, anorexia, bleeding).

--
